segments.text: In November of 63, I was finishing up my last extra semester.
This was the makeup semester to get my degree, and I had an English exam.
Of course, back in those days, the semester ended after Christmas sometime in early January.

and so this was like a mid mid semester exam that we're coming up for and I was on my way from the MSC over to take this I'd had lunch over at the MSC and was on my way over to take this midterm exam when I was walking across the campus and noticed how somber everyone and a lot of folks were listening to radios and everything and so I asked somebody as I was going along they said the president's been

has been shot at and looks like he has been hit so then I got on over and as I got to the academic building and started up somebody else had a little portable radio or maybe had come out of the building talking about it and I said well what happened to Kennedy and they said well he's been shot and he's at the hospital we don't know well by the time I got up to the classroom and sat down when the professor came in to start administering the exam
He said, fellas, I know this is going to be really distracting to you.
He said, the president has been shot.
Most of you know that, but we just got word that the president died.
So the president's been assassinated.
He said, but because of the timing and the scheduling that we have to go through, I can't dismiss the class.
He said, I'd like to do that, but we just can't do that because there's no makeup available.

so but I want you all to concentrate on this do the best you can and I'll take this into consideration and then if when you get your grades you want to come back one-on-one and do a retake or do some supplemental stuff to improve your scores he said I'll consider that and I thought that was a very

Enlightened way to do things and I always appreciated profs that were tough and demanding and expected you to learn stuff but also were flexible enough that you know if you came in and said you know I had a bad night or there's been a death in the family or sometimes even if you were it was your own fault you were making excuses sometimes if they saw you were willing to come in and
put some extra effort and that your grades were important to you, not only your grades, but actually learning something was important to you, they usually would accommodate you.
During that day, describe the student body in general, their attitudes, their values, their diversity, their economics.
What was the Aggie student body like?
My impression was it was just, it was normal.
Nothing really stands out.
It was just a reflection of the late 50s and the early 60s.
I know one of the things that was happening then was of course the Civil Rights Movement was in its embryonic stages then and some of the people got involved in that but

they weren't very many and a lot of people you know just kind of shrugged you know if there was a march in Selma or something that somebody said well you know it varied considerably among my the folks in my Sunday school class and at church the ideals were more enlightened because I mean after all if you're going to spend a lot of money and pay missionaries to do Christian work in Africa you know why would you
treat people in an unchristian-like way here in the United States.
I never really understood slavery and redneck bigotry anyway.

And in the summer of 63, between when my class graduated and I went back for my last semester to finish my English degree, I went to East Africa on a project called Operation Crossroads and spent several months doing a
a summer version of a Peace Corps-type project.

And yet when I was raising money for that in the spring of 63, I actually had one of my classmates' fathers ask me, you know, he said, well, how come you want to go to Africa and live with those niggers over there?
And so there were
Still redneck attitudes in East Texas, but I never really ran across that much among my generation of folks.

I mean, there were some with prejudices and some didn't want women or blacks coming to A&M, but most of them were, you know, kind of open and interested and kind of willing to evolve and just looking for leadership.
In economic background, generalize about the Aggies then.
I would say middle to lower middle class.
Of course, America's not supposed to have classes, but just economic strata.
And I guess really smart kids, if they had guidance, would have ended up at Rice or Harvard or MIT or whatever.
Stanford or someplace, if someone guided them.
I'd never ever, I'd never even considered all through high school a service academy.
Nobody had ever incurred, I didn't even know about it.
I might could have qualified, I don't know.
I might could have qualified for Rice if I had applied, I don't know.

I just, you know, I'd always wanted to be an Aggie, so a lot of times when people looked down on A&M back then, and maybe some of it still lingers today, when people say, well, it's just a little ag college in Backwater.

I don't really pay any attention to that because I think A&M's got plenty to be proud of and I think it's a world-class university and has been for years and years and maybe its focus has been more engineering and agriculture as opposed to math, political science, psychology or other things that other universities are known for but I think Aggies have done well representing themselves and competing all over the world and I don't think A&M
then or now has anything to apologize for and I think it's always great to want to be a little bit better and to get your reputation well known nationwide but I never
I never had any ideas that Aggies were low class or just farmers or hick hillbillies.
I always thought that was, I mean, there were.
There probably always will be some in that category.
And if you're looking to stereotype, you can always find some examples to support that.
As far as you knew in the student body when you were here, geographically, were they from small towns, country, big cities, or what?

You probably already know the answer to this, but I would say in the late 50s, early 60s, I would guess maybe 55, 45, maybe 60, 40 that they were from rural, small, medium-sized towns with the minority being from larger cities.
I think that probably has evolved.
It's probably closer to
50-50 or maybe 45-55 the other way where more from the larger size cities but I don't know you probably have a better answer on that than I do.
Was everybody accepted?
Did it matter where you were from?
What your dad did for a living?
Not as long as you behaved yourself and made an effort to join in and mix with the group.
Now if you were standoffish or if you felt

elite and holier than thou you wouldn't fit in very well or if you were so shy and introverted that you wouldn't participate you know but it just what it was your own attitude that made the difference.
Describe the religious activities in those days particularly describe the Baptist Student Union.
Where did it meet and how often?
Baptist Student Union was at Northgate on the main street.
What's the street?
It runs by the post office and runs by Hollick's and down there.
The First Baptist Church was on the right-hand side as you go north, and the Baptist Student Union was right across the street.
I'd usually go over there maybe one or two nights a week.

week for an hour or two for you know fellowship and maybe Bible study maybe a motivational speaker or something and I was usually over there at the church usually on Sunday mornings and a lot of times on Sunday evenings.
Was there a scheduled Sunday evening BSU event?
Usually those were, I'm trying to remember whether that was church-related, a training union.

Baptists usually have both the morning Sunday school and a training union Bible studies in the evening, and a lot of times they'll have a Bible study on Wednesday evenings, and then either a prayer meeting or
or a choir practice if you're in the choir.
And I did sing in the choir at the church.
And right now it's kind of a blur as to what was happening at the church and what was over across the street at the BSU.
It seemed like the BSU was more weeknight activity.
There might have been sometimes a Sunday evening activity over there.
But I remember signing up for a

there was actually a credit course in I can't remember if it was the Bible or comparative religion and Prof Smith was the one who taught that taught it right there at the BSU but it was sanctioned for credit but you didn't have to pay any tuition for it but you did have to meet you had to show up you had to take course to pass the test and everything but and I did take I believe I took
because I'd have to look on my transcript and see.
I was under the impression that it was for credit.
I'd have to look on my transcript to see if it was recognized by A&M.
I think it was.
Well, it was.
Yeah, okay.
All right, let's shift to athletics.
Describe a typical home games Saturday, football Saturday.
What time did you guys get up and get moving and so forth?
What was it?
I just remembered that home games were very, there was a lot of activity around.
We did, even the days leading up to it, there were yell practices.
We did the banner in the Grove.
It was in the Grove.
I thought at that point it always had been and always would be.
I mean, the Grove was one of the traditions.
And when I got back, came back to work here at A&M in early 91, I was kind of disappointed to see that the Grove had kind of passed into oblivion.
As a matter of fact, is it still there?
I believe it's still there, but it's not used very much.
I don't think it's used much at all.

So, but the other activities, the big canvas signs that hang from the dorm, the little caricatures and cartoons, the spirit signs, I remember having those laid out in one of our, well the only meeting room in the dorm.
In fact, it wasn't even big enough to hold the whole sign spread out.

you had to work on it in sections and some of the guys that were in architecture or might have had a natural artistic flair knew how to proportion these things so that they'd come out looking readable and legible and funny when you hung them on the dorm but that usually took several hours I remember working

a little bit on one of those, but I was not that artistically inclined, and had other things that I had to do at the MSC, so I didn't work on those very much, but I know my classmates did, spent a lot of time on those.
Where did you and your buddies at the games, where did y'all stand?
On the east side, kind of probably right about
end of the end zone line in the horseshoe and just the traditions of the 12th man and standing during the game and all that.
I don't remember much being unusual or unique about that other than what's typical of Aggie lore.
Do you remember any pranks or good bull during a football game or a football season?
you and your buddies?
I don't remember whether any of this happened during my four years or whether this was just hearsay from previous or past years but
You know, things like stealing Bevo or stealing the Baylor Bear or Mustangs.

I was not involved in any of that, and I heard a lot of war stories, and I didn't know if that was old eggs trying to incite the new eggs to new exploits or if that was something that had been done fairly recently.
Looking back on it now, I can't remember whether any of those were really noteworthy during my tenure there or not.
Did you ever help steal a footlocker?
on a senior's footlocker.
No, I didn't.
And yours didn't get stolen.
No.
Any favorite football game memories?
You remember any?
Well, I do remember when we played University of Texas, I believe that was in November of 62, because Jim Keller was the quarterback.

and there was a controversial play in the end zone that the call didn't go for A&M and Texas won the game as a result of it and I remember us being really irritated about that and as I recall I don't remember if television was widespread at that time or not or if it was still photos or something but the after the game evidence indicated that
that call should have gone for A&M, and it didn't.
But it's one of those things.
I'm not saying the refs threw it.
It was just a tough close call, and it went the wrong way.
As far as you knew, did athletes go to class in those days?
As far as I know, because I had some classes with some of them.
I don't know if they went regularly, or if they were cut a lot, or if they were tutored a lot.
I don't really know that much about how things went then.
I was kind of busy with my own career and with the MSC.
My sophomore year, sometime during the middle of the year, the chairman of the Great Issues Committee for some reason either resigned or left or dropped out or something.
So I became committee chairman for Great Issues as a sophomore.
And then that spring,
When the selections came up for the officers for the next year, I was elected to be vice president of the MSC Council and Directorate.
And so in September of 61, when they had the president's reception for the freshmen,

I was, as the vice president of the MSC Council and Directorate, I was standing there with Dean and Mrs. Hannigan, and my predecessor, Mike Schneider, was standing there with President and Mrs. Rutter as hundreds, if not thousands, of freshmen filed through the MSC.
And I can remember Mrs. Rutter telling us during a break and sitting there, and she was always a charming and gracious lady, she said,
She said, you know, I love these things, but man, I love to sit down and get off my feet for a few minutes.
What was your impression of Earl Rudder?
I was always very much impressed with him, not just because of his record, because I really didn't know that much about his record.
I knew he'd been with the Rangers and had led them up the cliffs of
Pointe d'Hoc, and I knew he was a war hero and had done that as a lieutenant colonel.

and then he had subsequently come back and I think he'd been a football coach and a mayor and out in Brady and then was elected to the or appointed to Texas Land Board Land Commissioner Land Commissioner and had cleaned up a pretty messy situation politically
And I knew that vaguely.
I knew more about it and had that reinforced in later years, but I knew a little bit about his background, and I knew he was a strong leader, no-nonsense type guy.
And he and Mrs. Rutter used to host fireside chats over at their home, the big wooden house that burned in December of 63.
In fact, I was over at the MSC and having lunch, and as we came out, we looked up, we could see the smoke, and were able to walk over there and saw that fire in progress.

But back in 61 and 62, when I was vice president and then later president of the MSC Council and Directorate, I was one of the student leaders invited over, I would say maybe once or twice a semester,
to their home or it might be on call if there was some issue or some incident that had happened that he wanted to, you know,
test the water, see what was happening, or maybe ask for our help in getting things calmed down.
We'd go over there, and Mrs. Rutter always served punch or tea, or not tea unless it was iced tea, but soft drinks and cookies.
She always had homemade cookies.
And we would talk in exchange, and just being able to express an opinion or to raise an issue I thought was...
was good and I always thought he was eminently reasonable.

I was kind of on the fence when the decisions came and that was during my tenure regarding both the non-compulsory membership in the cadet corps even for the first two years and introducing women to the campus and
I could see arguments pro and con on both sides, so I was kind of on the fence.
Also the name change came up during that time.
That was a lot of pivotal things happening in those years.
And of course I was even aware at that time, even though I never participated with it, of the, I believe that particular group was called, was it called the Century Council?
The Century Study.
The Century Study.
And I think the participants in that, sometimes maybe informally, were referred to as the Century Council.
And they were looking at what do we want A&M to be in 1976, which was the 100th anniversary.
And that was just less than a decade away.
It was time to plan ahead for that.
And so...
Sometimes when people were over there, I would make a comment or I would talk to them like John Lindsay.
I ran into John Lindsay over there and people on the MSC Council, you know, it's made up of students, some faculty members, and some former student members.
And I never made a formal presentation, never submitted a formal paper on anything, but I remember discussing things like that with a lot of different people.
being in a position and being respected and trusted enough to participate in those kind of discussions was always very highly motivating for me.
Did you have any impression of what Mr. Rutter's feelings were about those topics?
I always sensed that he was

neutral that was my feeling at the time he was probing he was he was asking people for pros and cons and yet in retrospect I think he must have been in favor of it because if he had been against it he could have squelched it just by not having it on the agenda as often as he did
And I was, in a way, I was kind of surprised, but then it kind of all fell into place when I found out years later about his secret meetings with the senator from Bryan.
Bill Moore.
Bill Moore, where sometimes one or the other would call or get a call, and they would arrange a rendezvous in some dark parking lot or some dark alleyway where they would pull up car to car.

open the window exchange information or strategy or or you know who's who needs to be contacted who needs to be brought online for this or that uh and and uh so in a way that that it doesn't surprise me but it does confirm that he was in favor of these or at least he was was won over I really don't know who the drivers were behind that whether it was Earl Rudder or whether there were other people
encouraging him to do that.
I kind of suspect that John Lindsay was a big motivator behind that.

I don't know if there were others and I don't know if he felt pressured to go along with the other powers behind the scene or whether it was his idea and he was using the powers behind the scene to bring public opinion around to the point where

it would be accepted or at least it would be neutral and leave it to his call but whoever did it however they did it it was effective and I think A&M is in a lot of respects is better for it in other respects I guess the argument could be made that even if A&M were smaller more focused more concentrated on engineering agriculture and training military officers
it still could be an important force.
Describe the role of the MSC Council President during that era.
What was the task of that slot?
I'm not sure how much real leadership and influence you had.
It was more like you were
helping to guide a lot of folks who were already self-motivated.

You were helping, you know, Wayne Stark implement all of the activities of the MSC, and obviously it's an important, it's a very important function to be the living room of the campus, to have nice places for you to bring visitors,
visit with your parents and to have extracurricular activities.
And you were a coordinator.
You were a coordinator.
You were a facilitator.
You did budgeting.
You did selection.
I think the most important thing was selecting the leadership for the next generation and finding people who were qualified
self-starting, self-motivated, because you really didn't have a lot of power to coerce or to force somebody to do something that they didn't want to do or weren't willing to do, but

you could if you knew someone was motivated and maybe were getting a little bit careless or maybe were being distracted by girlfriends or academic problems or core problems or something sometimes you could maybe help chat with them and encourage them or maybe get them to a counselor who had the authority to do something I don't remember any really big problems except for some

my junior year there were some problems with the student senate apparently there had been there were some the student senate president I guess that was also called the student body president had offices over in the YMCA and student government was kept separate from
the student union, which was the MSC activities.
And I think Wayne had wanted it that way.
I think he had probably seen enough in other campuses where student government and student union could become rivals, especially if they were two strong personalities.
And he just preferred that they be kept separate.

but the student senate, I believe Malcolm Hall was one of the, well he was the student body president my junior year and so he presided over the student senate and I remember one of their agenda items was to get space to move over to the MSC.
They wanted to be in the MSC because I think they were
I think they were feeling like second-class citizens, and they thought the student body president should be number one and have a place of prominence.
And they may be right.
I don't know.
I tried not to take a position one way or the other because I knew Mr. Stark was not in favor of that.
What were some, in the NSC task you had, what were some of your greatest frustration moments and positive moments?
Okay, one incident I remember.
It was a little bit of frustration, anxiety, and then relief.
The SCONA, I guess this was the spring of either 60 or 61, must have been 61, spring of 61.
For the first time, a black delegate was invited to SCONA.
By mistake.
And it may have been a mistake, but...
They invited Florida A&M not realizing it was a black school.
Well, no, this guy was, that may have happened in a subsequent year, but this guy was from Texas A&I.
They invited Texas A&I and they selected a black delegate or maybe had a black delegate volunteer and didn't feel like they were in a position to veto it.
And so Vance Shaw, I believe from Belton or Temple, somewhere over in Central Texas, was the student who was going to be coming up.
And in fact, that occasioned one of my visits to the Green Couch.
The first one I mentioned was when we got Dr. Paul Seiple for great issues.
But on this one, Mr. Stark had me in there.
I was not only vice president there.
I was not the only one.
There were several of us in there, but there was...
The vice president of the MSC is ex officio a member of the Student Senate and a member of the Executive Committee of SCONA.
And so we had some folks in there brainstorming about how to...
